<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="66" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,655,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[325,429,655,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[472,601,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[472,601,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was analyzed by Dr. R.W. Garrison and was found to be conspecific to 
<taxonomicName authority="in De Marmels &amp; Garrison (2005)" authorityName="in De Marmels &amp; Garrison" authorityYear="2005" box="[151,705,690,717]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrurum">
<emphasis box="[151,300,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. macrurum</emphasis>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="De Marmels, J. &amp; Garrison, R. W." box="[339,705,690,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" pagination="257 - 273" refId="ref15207" refString="De Marmels, J. &amp; Garrison, R. W. (2005) Review of the genus Leptagrion in Venezuela with new synonymies and description of a new genus, Bromeliagrion, and a new species, B. rehni (Zygoptera: Coenagrionidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 137, 257 - 273. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / n 04 - 096" type="journal article" year="2005">De Marmels &amp; Garrison (2005)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[844,972,691,716]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[844,972,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was included as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in De Marmels &amp; Garrison" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrurum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. macrurum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the present study, after analyzing all described species previously placed in 
<emphasis box="[1182,1430,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1876" box="[1182,1306,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">Leptagrion</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1315,1430,727,753]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" sensu="lato">sensu lato</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, I discovered that three groups of species are close regarding the morphology of cercus but very different in penile morphology, certain similarities are also found between the species of each group and a broader look at other structures was necessary to correctly separate the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
The shape of the junction between the posterior lobe of the prothorax and the middle lobe (angle of the junction and the shape of the lateral border of the posterior lobe) proved to be an important and reliable structure to be used together with the morphology of the cerci and penis and, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[825,951,943,968]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[825,951,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it was fundamental to separate this species from its congener 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in De Marmels &amp; Garrison" authorityYear="2005" box="[355,501,979,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrurum">
<emphasis box="[355,501,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. macrurum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as shown in 
<figureCitation box="[653,757,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,1329,1751]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[151,1437,1327,1754]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 9. Leptagrion bocainense: A—Prothorax, lateral view; B—Prothorax, dorsal view" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332349/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Figures 9</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[811,857,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1672,1696]" captionTargetBox="[151,1423,1227,1647]" captionTargetId="figure-51@8.[151,1436,1223,1649]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 11. Leptagrion vilelai: A—Prothorax, lateral view; B—Prothorax, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332355" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332355/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">11C</figureCitation>
(
<typeStatus box="[871,971,979,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[1007,1133,979,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[1007,1133,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<typeStatus box="[1187,1290,979,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<taxonomicName authorityName="in De Marmels &amp; Garrison" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrurum">L. macrurum</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
respectively) the junction is very different, confirming the position of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[994,1120,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[994,1120,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
A detailed study of the penis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[513,639,1051,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[513,639,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will likely show additional differences between these two species, unfortunately in Dr. Garrison’s illustrations (
<bibRefCitation author="De Marmels, J. &amp; Garrison, R. W." box="[621,959,1086,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" pagination="257 - 273" refId="ref15207" refString="De Marmels, J. &amp; Garrison, R. W. (2005) Review of the genus Leptagrion in Venezuela with new synonymies and description of a new genus, Bromeliagrion, and a new species, B. rehni (Zygoptera: Coenagrionidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 137, 257 - 273. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / n 04 - 096" type="journal article" year="2005">De Marmels &amp; Garrison 2005</bibRefCitation>
) the medio-longitudinal laminar process is not shown for both species (presented in this paper for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="in De Marmels &amp; Garrison" authorityYear="2005" box="[767,914,1123,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrurum">
<emphasis box="[767,914,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">L. macrurum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
